{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d754ea8a-e1fc-484d-8292-82cb523addd3","content":"\n\nIn .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle event mappings** on `MauiAppBuilder` in your `CreateMauiApp()` method:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` at the top.\n- The `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives ensure platform code only compiles on the correct target.\n- Each handler receives the native platform object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call native APIs directly if needed.\n- You can chain multiple events (e.g., `.OnPause(...).OnResume(...)`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a56af903-e8fc-4718-ae5d-331cd2d6674a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question, not a code task in the repository.","outputTokens":336},"id":"4181591a-2ef8-4c4c-8e3e-954311aafa65","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:45:29.660Z","parentId":"19f1fd1c-4a73-4550-8c5b-fa175d77b47b"}
